<h2>
    Top Trout Fishing Spots Near Portland
</h2>

<h3>
    <strong>1. Sandy River</strong>
</h3>
<p>
    Just ~20 minutes east of Portland, the <strong>Sandy River</strong> is a favorite for <strong>rainbow and cutthroat trout</strong>. Fish within deeper pools around structure like rocks and fallen logs. A family-friendly section is at Glen Otto Community Park.&nbsp;
</p>
<h3>
    <strong>2. Clackamas River</strong>
</h3>
<p>
    Another local gem, the <strong>Clackamas River</strong> supports <strong>rainbow and cutthroat trout</strong>, with some wild fish mixed in. Good spots include Carver Park and Milo McIver State Park near Estacada, ideal for both fly and spin anglers.&nbsp;
</p>
<h3>
    <strong>3. Eagle Creek</strong> <i>(tributary of the Clackamas)</i>
</h3>
<p>
    Accessible via Estacada, Eagle Creek is a small mountain stream rich in <strong>rainbow and cutthroat trout</strong>. Perfect for summer fly-fishing with light tackle.
</p>
<h3>
    <strong>4. Henry Hagg Lake</strong>
</h3>
<p>
    Located ~25 miles northwest near Forest Grove, this reservoir is <strong>stocked heavily with rainbow trout</strong> (including trophy-sized "brood" fish). Bank anglers, boaters, and trollers all do well using PowerBait, spinners, and small flashers.&nbsp;
</p>
<h3>
    <strong>5. Willamette River</strong>
</h3>
<p>
    Flowing through Portland, the <strong>Willamette</strong> is surprisingly productive for trout, especially near Mary S. Young Park in West Linn or under the St. Johns Bridge at Cathedral Park. Expect trout, salmon, steelhead, and sturgeon.&nbsp;
</p>
<h3>
    <strong>6. Trillium &amp; Timothy Lakes</strong>
</h3>
<p>
    Located in the Mt. Hood National Forest (~60–90 minutes east), these alpine lakes are stocked with rainbows and kokanee. Ideal for float-tube or bank fishing in scenic forest settings.
</p>
<h3>
    <strong>7. Tualatin Valley Ponds</strong>
</h3>
<p>
    If you're up for a quick trip, head to urban ponds in the Tualatin Valley—<strong>Bethany Pond</strong>, <strong>Commonwealth</strong>, and <strong>Progress Lake</strong>—all close to Beaverton and stocked with trout, bluegill, and bass.&nbsp;
</p>
<h2>
    When to Go
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Spring (Mar–May):</strong> Prime time on rivers and reservoirs during stocking.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Summer (June–Aug):</strong> Great for summer creek fly-fishing; early mornings are best.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Fall (Sept–Oct):</strong> Cooler evenings bring trout back to shallows.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Winter (Nov–Feb):</strong> Trout in reservoirs like Hagg and urban ponds remain active.
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    Gear &amp; Techniques
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Rivers &amp; Creeks:</strong> Use 4–6 lb fluorocarbon; small spinners, Rooster Tails, Kastmasters; bring a 7–8 ft spinning rod.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Lakes &amp; Reservoirs:</strong> PowerBait or salmon eggs under a bobber; spoons and inline spinners while trolling; medium spinning setup.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Fly Fishing:</strong> 4–6 wt rods with nymphs (PMDs, Pheasant Tails), dries like Elk Hair Caddis; summer midge hatches.
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    Quick Tips
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Explore multiple access points</strong> if one spot is crowded.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Use a float tube or small boat</strong> to reach deeper zones in Hagg and alpine lakes.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Check ODFW fishing regulations</strong>, bag limits, and stocking schedules online.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Warmwater weekend?</strong> Urban ponds and lakes often see less pressure and are ideal for families or beginners.
    </li>
</ul>

<p>
    &nbsp;
</p>

<p>
    Trout fishing near <strong>Portland</strong> offers amazing diversity: from classic rivers and hidden mountain lakes to urban ponds perfect for an afternoon outing. Tight lines and enjoy the adventure!
</p>

